language processing professor, and also does a 
lot of work in the mental health space. And we  

379
00:31:44,800 --> 00:31:52,960
were looking at a particular task where we 
were essentially trying to predict whether  

380
00:31:52,960 --> 00:31:59,920
people on the internet were suicidal based 
on a Reddit post actually. And it turns out  

381
00:31:59,920 --> 00:32:07,120
that comments like people saying, "I'm 
going to kill myself," stuff like that  

382
00:32:07,120 --> 00:32:12,880
are not actually indicative of suicidal intent. 
However, saying things like, "I feel trapped,  

383
00:32:12,880 --> 00:32:18,240
I can't get out of my situation are." And 
there's a term that describes this sentiment,  

384
00:32:18,240 --> 00:32:24,800
and the term is entrapment. It's that feeling 
trapped in where you are in life. And so,  

385
00:32:24,800 --> 00:32:33,360
we're trying to get GPT-4 at the time to class, 
classify a bunch of different posts as to  

386
00:32:33,360 --> 00:32:43,360
whether they had the entrapment in them or not.
And in order to do that, I talked to the model,  

387
00:32:43,360 --> 00:32:47,680
"Do you even know what entrapment is?" And it 
didn't know. And so, I had to go get a bunch  

388
00:32:47,680 --> 00:32:53,040
of research and paste that into my prompt to 
explain to it what entrapment was so I could  

389
00:32:53,040 --> 00:32:58,560
properly label that. And there's actually a bit 
of a funny story around that where I actually  

390
00:32:58,560 --> 00:33:05,280
took the original email the professor had sent me 
describing the problem and pasted that into the  

391
00:33:05,280 --> 00:33:12,400
prompt, and it performed pretty well. And then 
sometime down the line the professor was like,  

392
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:17,520
"Hey, probably shouldn't publish our personal 
information in the eventual research paper here."  

393
00:33:17,520 --> 00:33:22,880
And I was like, "Yeah, that makes sense."
So I took the email out and the performance  

394
00:33:22,880 --> 00:33:28,800
dropped off a cliff without that context, without 
that additional information. And then I was like,  

395
00:33:28,800 --> 00:33:34,080
"All right. Well, I'll keep the email and just 
anonymize the names in it." The performance  

396
00:33:34,080 --> 00:33:40,240
also dropped off a cliff with that. That is 
just one of the wacky oddities of prompting  

397
00:33:40,240 --> 00:33:46,400
and prompt engineering, there's just small things 
you change to have massive unpredictable effects,  

398
00:33:46,400 --> 00:33:51,120
but the lesson there is that including 
context or additional information  

399
00:33:51,120 --> 00:33:57,520
about the situation was super, super 
important to get a performance prompt.

400
00:33:57,520 --> 00:34:00,640
This is so fascinating. Imagine 
the professor's name had a lot  

