795
01:08:58,240 --> 01:09:02,320
and hopefully you're not asleep at the wheel. 
Hopefully you're paying attention to the gen AI  

796
01:09:02,320 --> 01:09:09,680
outputs. But as there's more and more trust built 
in the gen AIs, people just start to trust them. 

797
01:09:09,680 --> 01:09:14,640
But it's a very, very real problem right 
now and will become increasingly so as  

798
01:09:14,640 --> 01:09:20,080
more agents with potential real world 
harms and consequences are released.

799
01:09:20,080 --> 01:09:24,640
And I think it's important to say you work 
with OpenAI and other LLMs to close these  

800
01:09:24,640 --> 01:09:29,440
holes. They sponsor these events. They're 
very excited to solve these problems.

801
01:09:29,440 --> 01:09:32,320
Absolutely, yeah. They are 
very, very excited about it.

802
01:09:32,320 --> 01:09:37,120
From the perspective of say, a founder or a 
product team listening to this and thinking about,  

803
01:09:37,120 --> 01:09:42,800
"Oh, wow, how do we shut this down on our side? 
How do we catch problems?" Maybe first of all,  

804
01:09:42,800 --> 01:09:48,480
just what are common defenses that 
teams think work well that don't really.

805
01:09:48,480 --> 01:09:56,320
The most common technique by far that is used to 
try to prevent prompt injection is improving your  

806
01:09:56,320 --> 01:10:02,880
prompt and saying, in your prompt or maybe in the 
