807
01:10:02,880 --> 01:10:12,480
instructions. Be a good model." Stuff like that. 
This does not work. This does not work at all. 

808
01:10:12,480 --> 01:10:18,160
There's a number of large companies 
that have published papers proposing  

809
01:10:18,160 --> 01:10:21,920
these techniques, variants of these 
techniques. We've seen things like,  

810
01:10:23,360 --> 01:10:28,400
use some kind of separators between 
the system prompt and user input,  

811
01:10:28,400 --> 01:10:38,320
or put some randomized tokens around 
the user input. None of it works at all. 

812
01:10:39,040 --> 01:10:48,720
We ran this defense in, we ran a number of these 
prompt-based defenses in our Hackaprompt 1.0  

813
01:10:48,720 --> 01:10:55,920
Challenge back in May 2023. The defenses did 
not work then. They do not work now. Do you  

814
01:10:55,920 --> 01:11:00,160
want me to move on to the next technique that 
people use that's around [inaudible 01:11:00]-

815
01:11:00,160 --> 01:11:03,200
Yeah, I would love to, and then I 
want to know what works. But yeah,  

816
01:11:03,200 --> 01:11:04,960
what else doesn't work? This is great.

817
01:11:04,960 --> 01:11:15,360
So, the next step for defending is using some 
kind of AI guardrail. So you go out and you  

818
01:11:15,360 --> 01:11:21,120
find or make, I mean, there's thousands of 
options out there. An AI that looks at the  

819
01:11:21,120 --> 01:11:31,920
user input and says, "Is this malicious or not?"
This is a very limited effect against a motivated  

820
01:11:31,920 --> 01:11:38,880
hacker or AI red teamer, because a lot of 
these times they can exploit what I call  

821
01:11:38,880 --> 01:11:48,400
the intelligence gap between these guardrails and 
the main model where say I Base64 encode my input.  

822
01:11:49,600 --> 01:11:55,120
A lot of times the guardrail model won't even be 
intelligent enough to understand what that means. 

823
01:11:55,120 --> 01:12:01,040
It'll just be like, "This is gobbledygook. I guess 
it's safe." But then the main model can understand  

824
01:12:01,040 --> 01:12:08,720
and be tricked by it. So guardrails are a widely 
proposed used solution. There's so many companies,  

825
01:12:08,720 --> 01:12:15,920
so many startups that are building these, this 
is actually one of the reasons I'm not building  

826
01:12:15,920 --> 01:12:24,560
these. They just don't work. They don't work.
This has to be solved at the level of the AI  

827
01:12:24,560 --> 01:12:32,800
provider. And so I'll get into some solutions 
that work better as well as where to maybe apply  

828
01:12:32,800 --> 01:12:40,000
guardrails. But before doing so, I will also note 
that I have seen solutions proposed that are like,  

829
01:12:40,000 --> 01:12:45,120
"Oh, we're going to look at all of the prompt 
injection data sets out there. We're going to  

830
01:12:45,120 --> 01:12:52,480
find the most common words in them, and just 
