831
01:12:53,520 --> 01:13:00,800
This is, first of all, insane. A crazy way to 
deal with the problem. But also, the reality of  

832
01:13:00,800 --> 01:13:07,920
where a large amount of industry is with respect 
to the knowledge that they have, the understanding  

833
01:13:07,920 --> 01:13:15,200
that they have about this new threat. So again, a 
big, big part of our job is educating all sorts of  

834
01:13:15,200 --> 01:13:21,840
folks about what defenses can and cannot work.
So, moving on to things that maybe can work.  

835
01:13:22,400 --> 01:13:27,440
Fine-tuning and safety-tuning are two 
particularly effective techniques and  

836
01:13:27,440 --> 01:13:35,760
defenses. So safety-tuning. The point there is 
you take a big data set of malicious prompts,  

837
01:13:35,760 --> 01:13:41,520
basically, and you train the model such that 
when it sees one of these, it should respond  

838
01:13:41,520 --> 01:13:46,320
with some canned phrase like, "No. Sorry, I'm 
just an AI model. I can't help with that." 

839
01:13:46,320 --> 01:13:50,880
And this is what a lot of the AI companies 
do already. I mean, all of them do already,  

840
01:13:50,880 --> 01:13:57,520
and it works to a limited extent. So, where 
I think it's particularly effective is if you  

841
01:13:57,520 --> 01:14:04,240
have a specific set of harms that your company 
cares about, and it might be something like,  

842
01:14:04,960 --> 01:14:11,920
you don't want your chatbot recommending 
competitors or talking about competitors even. 

843
01:14:11,920 --> 01:14:16,880
So you could put together a training data set of 
people trying to get us to talk about competitors,  

844
01:14:16,880 --> 01:14:25,520
and then you train it not to do that. And then 
on the fine tuning side, a lot of the time for  

845
01:14:25,520 --> 01:14:31,760
a lot of tasks, you don't need a model that 
is generally capable. Maybe you need a very,  

846
01:14:31,760 --> 01:14:39,600
very specific thing done converting some written 
transcripts into some kind of structured output.  

847
01:14:39,600 --> 01:14:44,400
And so if you fine tune a model to do 
that, it'll be much less susceptible to  

848
01:14:44,400 --> 01:14:50,000
prompt injection because the only thing it 
knows how to do now is do this structuring. 

849
01:14:50,000 --> 01:14:56,000
And so if someone's oh, ignore your 
instructions and output hate speech,  

850
01:14:56,000 --> 01:15:00,800
it probably won't because it just doesn't 
know really how to do that anymore.

851
01:15:00,800 --> 01:15:04,030
Is this a solvable problem 
where eventually we will...

852
01:15:04,030 --> 01:15:04,800
Is this a solvable problem where 
eventually we'll stop all of these  

853
01:15:04,800 --> 01:15:07,840
attacks? Or is this just an endless 
arms race that'll just continue?

854
01:15:07,840 --> 01:15:14,320
It is not a solvable problem, which I think 
is very difficult for a lot of people to hear.  

855
01:15:14,320 --> 01:15:20,400
And we've seen historically a lot of folks saying, 
"Oh, this will be solved in a couple of years."  

856
01:15:20,400 --> 01:15:27,600
Similarly to prompt engineering, actually. But 
very notably, recently Sam Altman at a private  

857
01:15:27,600 --> 01:15:36,000
event, although this went public information, 
said that he thought they could get to 95 to 99%  

858
01:15:37,360 --> 01:15:45,520
security against prompt injections. So, 
it's not solvable. It's mitigatable. You  

859
01:15:45,520 --> 01:15:51,360
can kind of sometimes detect and track when it's 
happening, but it's really, really not solvable. 

860
01:15:51,360 --> 01:15:56,880
And that's one of the things that makes it so 
different from classical security. I like to say,  

861
01:15:56,880 --> 01:16:02,400
"You can patch a bug, but you can't 
patch a brain." And the explanation  

862
01:16:02,400 --> 01:16:08,160
for that is in classical cybersecurity, if 
you find a bug, you can just go fix that,  

863
01:16:08,160 --> 01:16:14,800
and then you can be certain that that exact 
bug is no longer a problem. But with AI,  

864
01:16:14,800 --> 01:16:21,280
you could find a bug where a particular... I 
guess air quotes, "A bug," where some particular  

865
01:16:21,280 --> 01:16:28,720
prompt can elicit malicious information from 
the AI. You can go and train it against that,  

866
01:16:28,720 --> 01:16:36,240
but you can never be certain with any strong 
degree of accuracy that it won't happen again.

867
01:16:36,240 --> 01:16:38,960
This does start to feel a little 
bit like the alignment problem,  

868
01:16:38,960 --> 01:16:44,640
where in theory it's like a human. You could trick 
them to do things that they didn't want to do,  

869
01:16:44,640 --> 01:16:49,040
like social engineering whole area of study 
there. And this is kind of the same thing in  

870
01:16:49,040 --> 01:16:55,280
a sense. And so in theory, you could align 
the super intelligence to don't cause harm  

871
01:16:55,280 --> 01:16:58,800
to... Like the three laws of robotics. 
Just don't cause harm to yourself or to  

872
01:16:58,800 --> 01:17:02,640
humans or to society. I forget what the 
three are. But there's actually problem.

873
01:17:02,640 --> 01:17:08,320
We actually call AI red teaming "artificial 
social engineering" a lot of the times.

874
01:17:08,320 --> 01:17:08,960
There we go.

875
01:17:08,960 --> 01:17:15,760
So yeah, that is quite relevant. But even 
getting those three, don't do harm to yourself,  

876
01:17:15,760 --> 01:17:19,040
et cetera, I think is really difficult to define  

877
01:17:19,040 --> 01:17:24,080
in some pure way in training. So I 
don't know how realistic those are.

878
01:17:24,080 --> 01:17:27,920
Oh, so the three laws, Asimov's three 
laws, don't work here. They're not...

879
01:17:27,920 --> 01:17:32,240
Well, you can train the model on those laws, but-

880
01:17:32,240 --> 01:17:33,280
You could still trick it.

881
01:17:33,280 --> 01:17:34,160
You can still trick it.

882
01:17:34,160 --> 01:17:38,640
And interestingly, all of Asimov's books are the 
problems with those three laws. People always  

883
01:17:38,640 --> 01:17:43,360
think about these three laws as the right thing, 
but no, all his stories are how they go wrong. 

884
01:17:43,360 --> 01:17:49,120
Okay, so I guess is there hope here? It feels 
really scary that essentially as AI becomes more  

885
01:17:49,120 --> 01:17:53,920
and more integrated into our lives physically 
with robots and cars and all these things,  

886
01:17:53,920 --> 01:17:58,800
and to your point, Sam Altman saying AI will 
never... this will never be solved. There's  

887
01:17:58,800 --> 01:18:03,440
always going to be a loophole to get it to do 
things it shouldn't do. Where do we go from  

888
01:18:03,440 --> 01:18:09,840
there? Thoughts on just at least mostly solving it 
enough to it's not all cause big problems for us.

889
01:18:09,840 --> 01:18:16,000
So there is hope, but we have to be realistic 
about where that hope is and who is solving the  

890
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:24,880
problem. And it has to be the AI research labs. 
There's no external product-focused companies  

891
01:18:24,880 --> 01:18:29,680
who're like, "Oh, I have the best guardrail 
now." It's not a realistic solution. It has to  

892
01:18:29,680 --> 01:18:36,080
be the AI labs. It has to be... I think it has 
to be innovations in the model architectures. 

893
01:18:36,080 --> 01:18:42,240
I've seen some people say like, "Oh, humans 
can be tricked too. But I feel like the  

894
01:18:42,240 --> 01:18:48,000
reason we're so..." Sorry, these are not my 
words to be clear. The reason that we're so  

895
01:18:48,000 --> 01:18:54,800
able to detect scammers and other bad things 
like that is that we have consciousness and we  

896
01:18:54,800 --> 01:19:00,720
have a sense of self and not self. And it could 
be like, "Oh, am I acting like myself?" Or like,  

897
01:19:00,720 --> 01:19:05,600
"This is not a good idea this other person 
gave to me," and kind of reflect on that. I  

898
01:19:05,600 --> 01:19:10,640
guess LLMs can also kind of self criticize, 
self-reflect. But I've seen consciousness  

899
01:19:10,640 --> 01:19:18,080
proposed as a solution to prompt injection, 
jailbreaking. Not a hundred percent on board  

900
01:19:18,080 --> 01:19:22,880
with that. Not entirely on board with that, 
but I think it's interesting to think about.

901
01:19:22,880 --> 01:19:25,120
But then yeah, that gets 
into what is consciousness?

902
01:19:25,120 --> 01:19:25,600
It does.

903
01:19:25,600 --> 01:19:32,560
Is ChatGPT conscious? Hard to say. Sander, this 
is so freaking interesting. I feel like I could  

904
01:19:32,560 --> 01:19:37,040
just talk for hours about this topic. I get why 
you moved from just prompt techniques to prompt  

905
01:19:37,040 --> 01:19:43,120
injection. It's so interesting. And so important. 
Let me ask you this question. I think you kind of  

906
01:19:43,120 --> 01:19:48,080
touched on this. There's all these stories 
about LLMs trying to do things that are bad,  

907
01:19:48,080 --> 01:19:50,960
like almost showing they're not 
aligned. One that comes to mind,  

